WEBVTT

00:32.980 --> 00:34.990
[HEART BEATING STEADILY]

00:54.610 --> 00:56.570
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

01:03.190 --> 01:04.150
[GROANS SOFTLY]

01:25.380 --> 01:26.340
[EXHALES]

01:31.910 --> 01:33.260
That was a long one.

01:38.090 --> 01:42.500
I don't suppose you can tell me
how it looks, can you?

01:42.700 --> 01:45.630
Unfortunately,
I'm just the technician.

01:45.830 --> 01:48.020
Your doctor will have
your results tomorrow.

01:49.840 --> 01:51.760
- Would you like some help to...
- Thank you very much.

01:52.670 --> 01:53.800
You're very kind.

02:03.030 --> 02:05.000
CHRIS: I mean, yeah,

02:05.200 --> 02:08.130
the cancer has brought
grief and pain

02:08.330 --> 02:11.300
and fear into my every
waking moment.

02:12.560 --> 02:16.920
GROUP LEADER: Okay, Chris.
Today is a gift.

02:17.120 --> 02:19.970
That's why they call it
the present.

02:20.170 --> 02:21.140
[JOHN SIGHS SOFTLY]

02:22.220 --> 02:23.280
Anyone else?

02:23.480 --> 02:24.930
[SIGHS WEARILY]

02:25.130 --> 02:26.590
Henry Kessler.

02:26.780 --> 02:28.200
Please.

02:28.400 --> 02:30.840
Stage four pancreatic.

02:31.490 --> 02:32.450
Terminal.

02:33.580 --> 02:36.670
That's what they tell me,
anyway, but...

02:39.940 --> 02:41.720
I'm gonna fight this
'til the end.

02:46.160 --> 02:47.810
How much time do I have?

02:51.470 --> 02:52.520
A year?

02:53.560 --> 02:56.400
Months at best.

02:56.600 --> 02:59.440
I still have a lot of work
that needs to be done.

02:59.640 --> 03:00.610
My advice?

03:02.260 --> 03:03.230
Retire.

03:03.430 --> 03:04.350
[CHUCKLES SOFTLY]

03:05.480 --> 03:07.500
You know, at this stage,

03:07.700 --> 03:10.240
everyone always searches
for a way out.

03:10.440 --> 03:14.020
But sometimes,
those who accept their fate,

03:14.220 --> 03:15.200
have an easier time.

03:15.400 --> 03:16.840
Easier time? What?

03:18.370 --> 03:19.460
Dying?

03:22.200 --> 03:26.770
So, your advice to me
is to die easy?

03:32.690 --> 03:33.650
[MONITOR BEEPING]

03:33.850 --> 03:34.740
[VENTILATOR HISSING]

03:34.940 --> 03:36.820
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

04:32.530 --> 04:33.920
[GASPS]

04:39.800 --> 04:41.500
[PANTING]

04:41.700 --> 04:44.840
Help! Hey! Help! Help, please!

04:47.020 --> 04:48.670
[BREATHING HEAVILY]

04:54.640 --> 04:57.740
JIGSAW: [OVER SPEAKER]
<i>I'd like to play a game.</i>

04:57.940 --> 05:01.640
<i>Perhaps one that addresses</i>
<i>those sticky fingers of yours.</i>

05:03.390 --> 05:07.910
<i>I've had my eyes on you</i>
<i>and I do not like what I see.</i>

05:09.430 --> 05:12.660
<i>Your job as a custodian</i>
<i>is a noble one.</i>

05:12.860 --> 05:15.410
<i>Sanitizing and sterilizing</i>
<i>the hospital...</i>

05:15.610 --> 05:16.620
[JANITOR WHIMPERING]

05:16.820 --> 05:18.760
<i>...helping patients</i>
<i>avoid sickness.</i>

05:18.960 --> 05:20.670
<i>But there is</i>
<i>a sickness inside you</i>

05:20.870 --> 05:22.200
<i>that needs to be excised.</i>

05:22.400 --> 05:23.540
[COUGHING]

05:23.740 --> 05:25.980
<i>You have the ability</i>
<i>to not only save</i>

05:26.180 --> 05:28.380
<i>your soul today,</i>
<i>but your sight.</i>

05:28.580 --> 05:29.990
[PANTING]

05:30.190 --> 05:32.250
<i>All you have to do is</i>
<i>click the dial</i>

05:32.450 --> 05:34.340
<i>across the five positions</i>

05:34.540 --> 05:37.340
<i>and you will live to see</i>
<i>another day.</i>

05:37.540 --> 05:39.560
<i>You have 60 seconds.</i>

05:39.760 --> 05:40.640
Help, please!

05:43.160 --> 05:45.210
[WHIMPERING]

05:46.910 --> 05:49.470
Help me! Please, please,
please. Help. Help!

05:50.260 --> 05:51.220
[BEEPS]

05:51.420 --> 05:53.970
- [BONE CRACKS]
- [SCREAMS]

05:54.170 --> 05:55.490
[TICKING]

05:55.690 --> 05:57.700
[GRUNTING]

06:02.400 --> 06:03.370
[BEEPS]

06:03.570 --> 06:05.580
- [BONE CRACKS]
- [SCREAMS]

06:09.360 --> 06:11.770
I can't! I can't, I can't!

06:11.970 --> 06:13.890
[CRYING] Please, no!

06:14.850 --> 06:15.980
[SCREAMING]

06:18.020 --> 06:19.160
[BEEPS]

06:20.160 --> 06:21.990
[SCREAMING]

06:24.900 --> 06:26.380
Fuck you!

06:29.250 --> 06:30.740
- [ALARM BUZZING]
- [SCREAMING]

06:30.940 --> 06:32.740
[MACHINE WHIRRING]

06:45.100 --> 06:46.500
[MACHINE WINDS DOWN]

06:46.700 --> 06:48.400
[CRYING]

06:50.670 --> 06:52.410
[CRYING ECHOES]

06:53.280 --> 06:55.240
[MONITOR BEEPING]

07:09.210 --> 07:10.430
Good choice.

07:14.730 --> 07:16.690
[SOMBER MUSIC PLAYING]

07:31.270 --> 07:32.890
BARISTA: Here you go, sir.

07:33.090 --> 07:34.060
Thank you.

07:48.110 --> 07:50.600
HENRY: Can I get
a blueberry scone, please?

07:52.990 --> 07:54.380
Oh, they look good.

07:56.120 --> 07:57.120
Thank you.

08:01.520 --> 08:02.480
Henry.

08:04.350 --> 08:05.530
[CHUCKLES SOFTLY]

08:05.730 --> 08:08.140
We were in the same
cancer support group.

08:08.340 --> 08:10.150
John Kramer.

08:10.350 --> 08:11.970
I remember you.

08:12.170 --> 08:13.920
[CHUCKLES] Hey, good to see you.

08:15.360 --> 08:16.400
And you as well.

08:19.190 --> 08:20.420
You look marvelous.

08:20.620 --> 08:23.330
Thank you. I... I...
I feel great.

08:23.530 --> 08:25.990
Correct me if I'm wrong,
but you were, uh...

08:26.190 --> 08:28.380
Yeah, stage four pancreatic.

08:28.580 --> 08:30.560
But now, four months later,

08:30.760 --> 08:33.860
I'm in complete remission.

08:35.420 --> 08:36.730
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

08:37.560 --> 08:38.510
How?

08:40.080 --> 08:43.530
It's a... it's a long story.

08:43.730 --> 08:46.790
[CHUCKLES SOFTLY]
I'd love to hear it.

08:46.990 --> 08:48.260
You got a minute to tell me?

08:49.180 --> 08:50.870
Sure. Sure.

08:56.840 --> 08:58.060
So, um,

08:58.260 --> 09:01.810
I read about a doctor,
a specialist of sorts.

09:02.010 --> 09:04.110
A Dr. Finn Pederson.

09:04.310 --> 09:06.900
He offered a treatment

09:07.100 --> 09:11.690
and it is a groundbreaking

09:11.890 --> 09:14.680
drug cocktail
combined with surgery.

09:20.510 --> 09:21.860
It's my war wound.

09:24.690 --> 09:27.050
I know it looks bad,

09:27.250 --> 09:30.310
but it was totally worth it.

09:30.510 --> 09:33.390
- [EXHALES] Yeah.
- [CHUCKLES]

09:35.000 --> 09:38.190
- Is it available here?
- No.

09:38.390 --> 09:40.890
No, no, the treatment's not
available in the States.

09:41.090 --> 09:43.840
The, uh, the medication
isn't approved by the FDA.

09:45.140 --> 09:47.320
Hell, it isn't approved
by anybody.

09:48.710 --> 09:51.280
I, um... I haven't
seen them since...

09:52.280 --> 09:54.070
since my treatment in Norway.

09:54.890 --> 09:55.890
But...

10:01.250 --> 10:03.470
this link...

10:06.080 --> 10:07.080
is still good.

10:12.870 --> 10:13.830
Hey, John,

10:16.130 --> 10:18.400
good luck, man. Okay?

10:18.600 --> 10:20.920
I'm... I'm rooting for you.

10:22.230 --> 10:23.540
Thank you.

10:23.740 --> 10:24.620
Take care.

10:33.450 --> 10:35.540
[JOHN SIGHS]

10:42.720 --> 10:44.740
Doctor, what exactly is
the procedure?

10:44.930 --> 10:48.390
Well, under the right
circumstances and with
the proper stimuli,

10:48.590 --> 10:51.180
genes can be turned on and
turned off like a light switch.

10:51.380 --> 10:53.270
TV HOST: <i>And you're targeting</i>
<i>the cancer cells?</i>

10:53.460 --> 10:55.350
FINN PEDERSON: <i>Exactly.</i>

10:55.550 --> 10:58.530
What we've managed to do is
to create a new cutting-edge
drug cocktail,

10:58.730 --> 10:59.970
along with surgery,

11:00.170 --> 11:02.490
to teach the malignant cells
to switch off.

11:02.690 --> 11:03.920
TV HOST: <i>Fascinating.</i>

11:04.570 --> 11:05.570
JOHN: Hmm.

11:06.440 --> 11:07.710
[KEYBOARD CLACKING]

11:17.500 --> 11:21.730
<i>My father, Dr. Finn Pederson,</i>
<i>was forced into hiding</i>

11:21.930 --> 11:26.210
<i>by corrupt governments</i>
<i>and their relationship</i>
<i>to big pharma.</i>

11:26.410 --> 11:28.390
Why?

11:28.590 --> 11:32.610
Because my father was
on the cusp of curing
dozens of diseases.

11:32.810 --> 11:36.790
<i>Which means no more need</i>
<i>for lifelong medication.</i>

11:36.990 --> 11:39.480
Can you imagine
what that implies?

11:41.700 --> 11:44.320
Well, the big drug companies
certainly can.

11:44.520 --> 11:48.760
<i>And I'm here to say</i>
<i>that this just cannot stand.</i>

11:48.960 --> 11:53.110
<i>So, while my father</i>
<i>continues to make further</i>
<i>improvements to his formula,</i>

11:53.310 --> 11:56.020
<i>I'm taking his treatment</i>
<i>on the road</i>

11:56.220 --> 11:57.420
<i>for more trials,</i>

11:57.620 --> 12:00.890
to save as many lives
as humanly possible.

12:15.770 --> 12:17.470
[CELL PHONE RINGING]

12:22.040 --> 12:23.430
[EXHALES]

12:33.570 --> 12:34.750
Who is this?

12:35.970 --> 12:37.850
This is Cecilia Pederson.

12:38.050 --> 12:39.280
Is this John Kramer?

12:40.190 --> 12:41.460
Yes, it is.

12:41.660 --> 12:43.290
CECILIA: <i>Good.</i>

12:43.490 --> 12:46.330
We received the email
with your medical records,
Mr. Kramer.

12:46.530 --> 12:48.120
Thank you for reaching out.

12:48.320 --> 12:51.300
<i>I'm sifting through</i>
<i>potential candidates</i>
<i>for our program.</i>

12:51.500 --> 12:53.250
So, I'm calling you now,

12:53.450 --> 12:55.640
because we have spots opening
for treatment in about
three months.

12:56.990 --> 12:58.250
[SIGHS WEARILY]

13:01.080 --> 13:02.340
Mr. Kramer?

13:03.040 --> 13:04.260
Uh, yes, I'm here.

13:05.780 --> 13:07.780
You don't have three months,
do you?

13:09.960 --> 13:11.710
<i>Okay, listen...</i>

13:11.910 --> 13:13.800
I'm currently working in Mexico.

13:14.000 --> 13:16.760
Oslo has become
too difficult for us.

13:16.960 --> 13:18.850
But we have a team
of specialists here

13:19.050 --> 13:21.720
who share our belief
in the Pederson method

13:21.920 --> 13:24.240
and I've gathered
a group of eligible patients

13:24.440 --> 13:26.640
to start treatment
a week from now.

13:26.840 --> 13:28.540
<i>I think I could add</i>
<i>one more spot.</i>

13:29.330 --> 13:30.810
<i>If you're interested.</i>

13:31.850 --> 13:33.020
Yes, I'm interested.

13:34.070 --> 13:35.120
Henry Kessler...

13:35.320 --> 13:36.430
<i>referred me to you.</i>

13:36.630 --> 13:40.600
Henry. He's doing well.
I'm so pleased.

13:41.470 --> 13:42.870
I wonder if you could...

13:43.070 --> 13:45.130
could you tell me a little more
about the treatment?

13:45.330 --> 13:47.180
CECILIA: <i>Of course.</i>

13:47.380 --> 13:51.010
It's a two-prong treatment
that uses my father's
Xaxiophenol cocktail.

13:51.210 --> 13:56.750
And in your case, it would be
combined with a cranial surgery
to clear the tumor.

13:56.950 --> 13:59.630
When both are used together,
the results have been stunning.

13:59.820 --> 14:01.980
<i>Over 90% success rate.</i>

14:02.180 --> 14:03.280
<i>I know it's a long trip,</i>

14:03.480 --> 14:06.850
Mr. Kramer,
especially in your condition,

14:07.050 --> 14:10.110
but I want you to know
that we found a very
beautiful location

14:10.310 --> 14:12.680
for our clinic
outside Mexico City.

14:12.880 --> 14:14.550
It's in a
well-off-the-grid area,

14:14.750 --> 14:18.600
in the countryside
where you can have
safety and privacy.

14:18.800 --> 14:22.600
<i>We'll also, of course,</i>
<i>arrange for a trusted</i>
<i>driver at your arrival.</i>

14:22.800 --> 14:24.390
What date did you have in mind?

14:24.590 --> 14:27.310
The 5th, Friday after next.

14:27.500 --> 14:29.120
I think I could make that.

14:30.560 --> 14:32.520
[MELANCHOLY MUSIC PLAYING]

14:40.790 --> 14:41.830
[CAR HONKING]

14:46.400 --> 14:48.500
- J. Kramer? Yeah?
<i>- Si.</i>Yes.

14:48.700 --> 14:51.160
I'm Diego. Welcome to Mexico.

14:51.350 --> 14:53.640
Allow me, sir. Please. This way.

14:53.840 --> 14:56.410
- [JOHN COUGHS]
- There you go.

15:00.550 --> 15:01.820
DIEGO: Take a look at that.

15:02.020 --> 15:04.260
That's the Metropolitan
Cathedral.

15:04.450 --> 15:07.130
That's the revolutionary
memorial.

15:07.330 --> 15:09.650
That's the Angel
of Independence.

15:09.850 --> 15:12.600
Take a look at that.
Isn't it beautiful?

15:14.560 --> 15:16.010
Hey, J.

15:16.210 --> 15:20.360
That, my friend, that's the old
Aztec statue of Tlaloc.

15:20.560 --> 15:21.660
That's where the priests

15:21.860 --> 15:23.540
chop the hearts
out of their subjects

15:23.730 --> 15:25.100
and roll them down the stairs.

15:25.300 --> 15:26.930
[DIEGO CHUCKLES]

15:27.130 --> 15:29.630
Every day, a tourist wants me
to take them here.

15:29.830 --> 15:31.140
Very strange.

15:50.470 --> 15:51.690
Hey, J.

15:51.890 --> 15:52.820
You okay?

15:57.340 --> 15:59.210
[MEN YELLING INDISTINCTLY
IN SPANISH]

16:01.520 --> 16:02.920
[IN ENGLISH] Get out!

16:03.120 --> 16:06.130
[MAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY
IN SPANISH]

16:09.140 --> 16:10.230
[IN ENGLISH] What's your name?

16:10.970 --> 16:12.450
John Kramer.

16:12.650 --> 16:15.940
Lie to me again and I'll empty
this chamber in your eye.

16:16.140 --> 16:18.280
I'm not lying.
My name is John Kramer.

16:20.930 --> 16:23.460
Not to worry, <i>senor</i>
Kramer, you're fine.

16:23.660 --> 16:26.770
You're safe. Come with me.
Come, come.

16:26.970 --> 16:29.850
Here. Welcome. Watch your head.

16:53.920 --> 16:54.920
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

16:55.790 --> 16:57.240
[IN ENGLISH] Your room.

16:57.440 --> 16:58.750
Here. Come.

17:00.450 --> 17:01.680
[KNOCKING AT DOOR]

17:01.880 --> 17:03.450
It's here. Good luck.

17:10.330 --> 17:11.330
<i>Si?</i>

17:13.590 --> 17:15.940
[IN ENGLISH] I am John Kramer.

17:17.070 --> 17:18.030
Come.

17:19.080 --> 17:20.030
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

17:28.740 --> 17:30.310
[IN ENGLISH] I... Gabriela.

17:38.310 --> 17:39.490
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

17:41.010 --> 17:42.360
<i>Mi familia.</i>

17:46.840 --> 17:47.840
[IN ENGLISH] Come.

17:49.320 --> 17:50.540
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

17:56.240 --> 17:57.990
[IN ENGLISH] Sleep. Sleep here.

17:58.190 --> 18:00.070
Dr. Cecilia Pederson?

18:00.940 --> 18:01.990
Ah. <i>Si.</i>

18:03.560 --> 18:07.520
[IN ENGLISH]
She saved life. My life.

18:10.560 --> 18:12.390
I get. I get now.

18:26.490 --> 18:29.020
Mr. Kramer, welcome.

18:32.720 --> 18:34.770
[CHUCKLES SOFTLY]

18:34.970 --> 18:39.080
That was quite a reception
that I got on the way out here.

18:39.280 --> 18:40.720
Oh, our welcome wagon?

18:41.770 --> 18:43.560
I know, I'm sorry.

18:43.760 --> 18:47.260
But we've had to beef up
the security wherever we go.

18:47.460 --> 18:50.220
The big drug companies
are always one step behind

18:50.420 --> 18:54.170
and so we must keep our location
secret from everyone, even you.

18:55.870 --> 18:56.840
Come.

18:57.030 --> 18:58.780
I want you to meet the team.

19:07.360 --> 19:09.190
- [MAN SPEAKING SPANISH]
- BOY: [IN ENGLISH] Yeah?

19:10.450 --> 19:14.460
That's Carlos.
Our local football star.

19:14.660 --> 19:16.450
His father is the caretaker.

19:19.070 --> 19:20.280
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

19:24.680 --> 19:26.380
[CARLOS GRUNTING]

19:28.420 --> 19:30.600
[FOOTBALL THUDDING]

19:39.830 --> 19:42.750
[IN ENGLISH] This used to be
a chemical factory
back in the day.

19:42.950 --> 19:44.870
[WATER DRIPPING]

19:48.400 --> 19:50.360
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

20:19.390 --> 20:20.650
CECILIA: Mateo.

20:21.390 --> 20:22.960
Hello, Doctor.

20:23.160 --> 20:24.710
CECILIA: This is John Kramer.

20:24.910 --> 20:27.010
Very nice to meet you,
Mr. Kramer, and welcome
to our clinic.

20:27.210 --> 20:28.830
You're in very good hands
with us.

20:29.570 --> 20:30.970
Hmm.

20:31.170 --> 20:33.580
Mateo is an anesthesiologist
at Hospital Alto Prado.

20:33.780 --> 20:38.070
He did his residency
at Johns Hopkins and has
worked a lot with my father.

20:38.270 --> 20:39.500
- Yes.
- He'll be helping out

20:39.700 --> 20:40.850
with your surgery tomorrow.

20:41.050 --> 20:42.550
Thank you.

20:42.750 --> 20:45.200
- I'll be right here
if you need anything.
- Thank you.

20:50.720 --> 20:53.300
This is Valentina,
one of our nurses.

20:53.500 --> 20:56.300
She'll be taking some scans
and drawing some blood,

20:56.500 --> 20:59.350
all in preparation for the
injection therapy later today.

20:59.550 --> 21:01.790
Mr. Sears' vitals look good.

21:01.990 --> 21:03.830
He's cleared for release.

21:04.030 --> 21:05.000
Wonderful.

21:06.650 --> 21:08.870
Parker Sears, John Kramer.

21:11.660 --> 21:14.100
Thyroid cancer, advanced. You?

21:14.300 --> 21:15.830
Uh, brain.

21:16.660 --> 21:19.370
Ah. [CHUCKLES] You win.

21:19.570 --> 21:20.710
[COUGHING]

21:23.280 --> 21:26.190
Sorry, they cut me open
yesterday.

21:27.240 --> 21:29.380
Took out a tumor
the size of my knob.

21:29.580 --> 21:31.770
I'm just about to start
the cocktail.

21:31.970 --> 21:33.820
Mutated natural killer cells.

21:34.020 --> 21:36.340
They're a type of
cytotoxic lymphocyte.

21:36.540 --> 21:38.160
Developed by my father.

21:39.250 --> 21:40.560
Good luck, John.

21:42.250 --> 21:44.180
Thank you.

21:44.380 --> 21:46.830
CECILIA: So, we've arranged
for you to stay at a hotel.

21:47.030 --> 21:48.130
Shall we begin?

21:54.700 --> 21:56.050
Please, don't move.

21:59.880 --> 22:01.500
[SIGHS]

22:01.700 --> 22:02.800
[BEEPS]

22:03.000 --> 22:04.230
[MACHINE WHIRS]

22:07.410 --> 22:08.640
[MACHINE WHIRS]

22:08.840 --> 22:11.250
CECILIA: <i>So, Mr. Kramer...</i>

22:11.450 --> 22:14.070
- What do you do?
Like, for a living?
- John.

22:14.850 --> 22:16.640
Please, call me John.

22:16.840 --> 22:18.860
And what do you do, John?

22:19.060 --> 22:22.770
I've been a civil engineer and
an architect most of my life.

22:23.600 --> 22:24.560
Now, I...

22:26.730 --> 22:27.910
have a few hobbies.

22:28.910 --> 22:29.910
Hmm.

22:30.690 --> 22:31.650
Let me guess.

22:32.650 --> 22:34.570
Classic car renovation.

22:34.770 --> 22:36.010
[CHUCKLES SOFTLY]

22:36.210 --> 22:38.320
- [CHUCKLES] No?
- No.

22:38.520 --> 22:39.490
I, uh...

22:39.690 --> 22:42.270
I help people overcome
inner obstacles.

22:43.880 --> 22:46.400
Help them make positive
changes in their lives.

22:47.140 --> 22:48.970
Like a life coach, yeah?

22:50.190 --> 22:51.320
Something like that.

22:52.060 --> 22:53.990
CECILIA: Sounds nice.

22:54.180 --> 22:56.940
I can't think of anything more
important than helping others.

22:58.150 --> 22:59.460
Yeah.

23:01.680 --> 23:03.170
Tequila.

23:03.370 --> 23:04.330
For good luck.

23:07.080 --> 23:08.340
JOHN: Thank you, Gabriela.

23:09.120 --> 23:10.120
<i>De nada.</i>

23:11.300 --> 23:13.350
CECILIA: It's a local favorite.

23:13.550 --> 23:14.830
You can't drink it now, though.

23:15.030 --> 23:16.300
Not before surgery.

23:21.740 --> 23:24.530
"My sun sets to rise again."

23:26.920 --> 23:28.790
Your sun is rising again, John.

23:31.140 --> 23:32.410
We will make sure of it.

23:43.980 --> 23:44.980
[EXHALES]

23:46.200 --> 23:47.940
[HAMMERING IN DISTANCE]

23:57.210 --> 23:59.430
[SPANISH MUSIC PLAYING
OVER RADIO IN DISTANCE]

24:01.170 --> 24:03.390
[HAMMERING CONTINUES]

24:20.930 --> 24:22.150
[CLANKING]

24:23.980 --> 24:25.460
You speak English, Carlos?

24:26.160 --> 24:28.170
<i>Que?</i>

24:28.370 --> 24:30.510
[IN ENGLISH] That's about
as good as my Spanish.

24:33.120 --> 24:34.560
How do you say "pull"?

24:37.300 --> 24:39.470
Pull, pull. Pull.

24:41.690 --> 24:42.650
<i>Jalar.</i>

24:43.830 --> 24:44.780
<i>Jalar.</i>

24:47.790 --> 24:50.280
Excellent. <i>Jalar.</i>

24:50.470 --> 24:51.400
[JOHN GRUNTS]

24:56.790 --> 24:57.800
<i>Gracias.</i>

25:00.890 --> 25:03.070
And who performs the surgery?

25:03.270 --> 25:05.160
Dr. Ramone Cortez.

25:05.360 --> 25:07.510
Also at Alto Prado.

25:07.710 --> 25:10.770
He's the best neurosurgeon
in 2,000 miles.

25:10.970 --> 25:14.170
He's the doctor I'd use
if my own family
was on the table.

25:14.370 --> 25:17.520
Now, we'll be performing
an "awake craniotomy."

25:17.720 --> 25:21.350
This means that you'll be
floating in and out
of consciousness...

25:21.550 --> 25:24.610
[ECHOING] ...so that we can do
function mapping...

25:24.810 --> 25:26.700
<i>This allows us to monitor</i>
<i>your abilities,</i>

25:26.900 --> 25:28.880
<i>so that we don't touch</i>
<i>any part of your brain</i>

25:29.080 --> 25:31.130
<i>that might affect speech</i>
<i>or movement...</i>

25:35.010 --> 25:37.670
[SHAVER BUZZING]

25:37.870 --> 25:40.010
[EERIE MUSIC PLAYING]

25:49.280 --> 25:50.630
[DR. CORTEZ SPEAKING SPANISH]

25:52.760 --> 25:54.860
[INDISTINCT CONVERSATION]

25:55.060 --> 25:57.120
[BREATHING DEEPLY]

25:57.320 --> 25:59.250
[MONITOR BEEPING]

26:07.390 --> 26:08.880
DR. CORTEZ: Mr. Kramer...

26:09.080 --> 26:10.690
Can you please wiggle
your fingers?

26:11.740 --> 26:14.360
Good. Motor function is clear.

26:14.560 --> 26:15.610
Suction vac, please.

26:16.610 --> 26:18.010
[DR. CORTEZ SPEAKING SPANISH]

26:28.100 --> 26:29.970
[BREATHING DEEPLY]

26:45.600 --> 26:47.560
[IN ENGLISH] Valentina,
will you move...

26:49.690 --> 26:51.170
VALENTINA: Right, right, right.

26:58.050 --> 27:00.000
[EKG MACHINE BEEPING]

27:06.140 --> 27:09.070
MATEO: Okay, great.
We're gonna
put you back to sleep.

27:09.270 --> 27:11.290
I'm gonna count down from ten.

27:11.490 --> 27:12.410
Ten...

27:13.410 --> 27:15.760
nine, eight...

27:16.460 --> 27:18.940
<i>seven, six...</i>

27:26.860 --> 27:27.820
Hi, there.

27:29.730 --> 27:30.730
You did great.

27:32.080 --> 27:33.920
Where are we?

27:34.120 --> 27:36.530
We're two blocks away
from Mateo's hospital.

27:36.730 --> 27:38.350
In case you need a transfusion.

27:39.220 --> 27:40.350
I got your bloodwork.

27:45.270 --> 27:47.400
Hemoglobin's normal.

27:50.230 --> 27:51.580
It all looks good, John.

27:52.360 --> 27:53.620
It all looks good.

27:55.840 --> 27:56.800
Now...

27:57.800 --> 27:59.550
Drink two a day.

27:59.750 --> 28:01.340
One in the morning
and one at night.

28:01.540 --> 28:02.950
Okay.

28:03.150 --> 28:04.730
CECILIA: In addition
to my father's treatment,

28:04.930 --> 28:08.330
it contains a painkiller
you'll need for the next
seven days.

28:09.510 --> 28:11.080
And after that,
what happens then?

28:12.860 --> 28:14.470
Your whole life happens then.

28:15.210 --> 28:17.520
[BREATHES DEEPLY]

28:18.520 --> 28:20.700
[CHUCKLES SOFTLY]

28:20.900 --> 28:23.090
I never got a chance
to say goodbye to Gabriela.

28:23.960 --> 28:25.100
Or, any of the others.

28:25.300 --> 28:26.670
I'll send them your best.

28:26.870 --> 28:28.670
Don't get your head wet.

28:28.870 --> 28:30.230
The bandage is anti-bacterial.

28:30.430 --> 28:32.930
It will stave off infection.

28:33.130 --> 28:36.240
Valentina will swing by
to keep an eye on it for you.

28:36.440 --> 28:37.680
Get some rest now, John.

28:37.880 --> 28:38.760
Okay.

28:40.980 --> 28:43.120
Dr. Pederson,
just so you know...

28:43.320 --> 28:45.630
I'll wire the second half
of the payment tomorrow morning.

28:46.500 --> 28:47.500
Thank you, John.

28:49.240 --> 28:50.850
Have a good life, John.

28:52.730 --> 28:55.120
A long, good life.
[CHUCKLES SOFTLY]

29:00.950 --> 29:01.950
[SIGHS]

29:06.870 --> 29:08.790
[HOPEFUL INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC
PLAYING]

29:18.710 --> 29:20.670
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

30:01.580 --> 30:03.500
Do you have a gift card?

30:03.700 --> 30:06.190
It's for a friend. Thank you.

30:19.600 --> 30:21.510
[HOPEFUL INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC
CONTINUES]

30:46.880 --> 30:48.840
<i>Un momento, por favor.</i>

30:51.240 --> 30:53.060
[GROANS SOFTLY]

31:01.640 --> 31:03.640
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

31:06.210 --> 31:07.160
[IN ENGLISH] Hello?

31:11.210 --> 31:12.300
Gabriela?

31:34.150 --> 31:35.580
[FLIPS SWITCH]

31:43.680 --> 31:45.680
[TENSE MUSIC PLAYING]

32:24.590 --> 32:26.340
<i>Hello, and welcome</i>

32:26.540 --> 32:27.510
<i>to section five</i>

32:27.710 --> 32:29.430
<i>in our neurosurgery series.</i>

32:29.630 --> 32:32.730
<i>The human brain is a mystery,</i>
<i>hundreds of millions...</i>

32:36.910 --> 32:39.920
CECILIA: <i>We'll be performing</i>
<i>an "awake craniotomy."</i>

32:40.120 --> 32:43.300
<i>This means that you'll be</i>
<i>floating in and out</i>
<i>of consciousness.</i>

32:46.050 --> 32:47.270
DR. CORTEZ: Valentina...

32:47.470 --> 32:48.920
VALENTINA: Right, right, right.

32:53.970 --> 32:55.970
[TENSE MUSIC CONTINUES]

33:28.870 --> 33:30.360
CECILIA:
<i>Have a good life, John.</i>

33:30.560 --> 33:32.880
<i>A long, good life.</i>

33:33.080 --> 33:35.180
[CECILIA'S VOICE CONTINUES
DISTORTED]

33:40.320 --> 33:41.670
[JOHN SCREAMS]

33:47.370 --> 33:49.420
DIEGO: Hey, guys.

33:49.620 --> 33:53.640
Did you know that when
the Aztecs roll the heart
of their victim down the stairs

33:53.840 --> 33:57.260
people will take them home
and display them like ornaments?

33:57.460 --> 34:00.170
In their fucking houses.
Yeah. [CHUCKLES]

34:00.370 --> 34:03.650
TOURIST 1: Nice.
DIEGO: Yes, sir,
welcome to Mexico.

34:04.560 --> 34:08.000
Okay, so here we are.

34:09.260 --> 34:11.780
This is the Tlaloc statue.
Okay?

34:12.960 --> 34:15.100
Huh. Thank you, man.
Have a good one.

34:15.300 --> 34:16.410
TOURIST 2: Of course, man.
Thanks.

34:16.610 --> 34:18.450
[SIGHS]

34:18.650 --> 34:20.580
[SHUTS ENGINE]

34:20.780 --> 34:22.660
[PEOPLE TALKING INDISTINCTLY
IN SPANISH]

34:26.230 --> 34:27.190
Hello.

34:28.500 --> 34:29.450
<i>Buenas noches.</i>

34:32.500 --> 34:33.900
[JOHN SPEAKING]

34:34.100 --> 34:35.020
[DIEGO SCREAMS]

34:41.030 --> 34:42.080
[COUGHS, GROANS]

34:44.730 --> 34:46.170
[TENSE MUSIC PLAYING]

34:47.780 --> 34:49.780
[WHIMPERING]

34:51.820 --> 34:53.390
[CRYING]

34:56.050 --> 34:58.090
[SCREAMS IN SPANISH] <i>Ayuda!</i>

35:01.180 --> 35:03.100
<i>Ayuda!</i>

35:05.010 --> 35:06.320
[GROANS IN PAIN]

35:08.880 --> 35:09.890
Kramer?

35:10.970 --> 35:12.110
[IN ENGLISH] Hey, man.

35:13.240 --> 35:14.860
I've told you
what you wanted to know!

35:15.060 --> 35:17.080
I fucking told you
who you're looking for!

35:17.280 --> 35:18.160
[CURSES IN SPANISH]

35:18.360 --> 35:20.290
[PANTING]

35:21.680 --> 35:23.340
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

35:23.540 --> 35:25.340
[PANTING]

35:25.860 --> 35:27.120
[GRUNTS]

35:38.090 --> 35:39.480
[MUTTERING]

35:40.920 --> 35:41.920
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

35:44.010 --> 35:46.100
Kramer. Kramer!

35:47.660 --> 35:49.140
[YELLING IN SPANISH]

35:50.360 --> 35:51.970
[BREATHING HEAVILY]

35:58.670 --> 36:01.500
JIGSAW: [ON TAPE]
<i>Hello, Diego.</i>
<i>Or, should I call you...</i>

36:02.720 --> 36:04.600
<i>Dr. Cortez?</i>

36:04.800 --> 36:07.390
<i>I'd like to play a game.</i>

36:07.590 --> 36:10.550
<i>Attached to your arms</i>
<i>are two explosive devices.</i>

36:11.640 --> 36:13.390
<i>Pipe bombs.</i>

36:13.590 --> 36:17.700
<i>Think of the explosives</i>
<i>as a sort of cancer.</i>

36:17.900 --> 36:22.710
<i>A malignancy that must be</i>
<i>cut out for you to survive.</i>

36:22.910 --> 36:26.360
<i>The blades cannot cut through</i>
<i>the galvanized cable.</i>

36:26.560 --> 36:29.970
<i>But they can slice through</i>
<i>flesh and muscle,</i>

36:30.170 --> 36:32.930
<i>allowing you to cut</i>
<i>the cancer away.</i>

36:33.130 --> 36:35.550
<i>Live, or die.</i>
<i>The choice is yours.</i>

36:35.740 --> 36:37.100
[TIMER BEEPS]

36:38.800 --> 36:40.900
No, no, no. No, no, no.

36:41.100 --> 36:42.370
- Kramer.
- [TIMER BEEPING]

36:42.890 --> 36:43.860
Kramer!

36:44.060 --> 36:45.860
Kramer!

36:46.060 --> 36:47.770
Kramer!

36:47.970 --> 36:50.460
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

36:54.640 --> 36:57.170
[PANTING]

36:59.430 --> 37:01.300
[MUTTERING]

37:11.310 --> 37:13.270
[TENSE MUSIC PLAYING]

37:33.860 --> 37:35.810
[TIMER BEEPING]

37:40.430 --> 37:41.910
[GRUNTING]

37:53.000 --> 37:54.570
[STRAINING]

38:03.150 --> 38:04.800
[EXCLAIMING IN PAIN]

38:07.670 --> 38:09.720
[TENSE MUSIC CONTINUES]

38:14.720 --> 38:16.070
[SCREAMS]

38:22.860 --> 38:24.170
[BREATHING HEAVILY]

38:30.870 --> 38:32.440
[GRIMACING IN PAIN]

38:35.700 --> 38:37.700
[CRYING]

38:44.800 --> 38:46.360
[SCREAMING IN PAIN]

39:08.430 --> 39:10.390
[CRYING]

39:28.320 --> 39:30.100
[GROANING]

39:36.190 --> 39:37.760
You're gonna be okay.

39:40.720 --> 39:41.820
<i>Detective...</i>

39:42.020 --> 39:44.290
I could use your assistance...

39:45.940 --> 39:50.910
in locating some people that are
in need of our services.

39:51.110 --> 39:53.040
[DANCE MUSIC PLAYING]

40:07.490 --> 40:09.400
[BOTH SPEAKING IN SPANISH]

40:12.270 --> 40:13.750
[VALENTINA CHUCKLES SENSUOUSLY]

40:16.540 --> 40:18.280
Okay. <i>Vamonos.</i>

40:23.980 --> 40:26.240
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

40:44.740 --> 40:45.740
[SCOFFS]

40:46.740 --> 40:49.660
- [SPEAKING SPANISH]
- [SCREAMS]

40:58.060 --> 41:00.240
- [SCREAMING]
- [GRUNTING]

41:09.510 --> 41:11.460
[PANTING]

41:15.990 --> 41:17.690
[WHIMPERS]

41:26.910 --> 41:28.480
[SCREAMING]

41:30.440 --> 41:32.440
[DOGS BARKING]

41:38.010 --> 41:39.140
[DOOR CLOSES]

41:42.840 --> 41:43.800
[SPEAKING IN SPANISH]

41:49.070 --> 41:50.020
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

42:08.300 --> 42:09.300
Mateo?

42:14.700 --> 42:15.660
[IN ENGLISH] Hey.

42:17.920 --> 42:19.620
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

42:22.580 --> 42:23.800
GABRIELA: Mm.

42:34.070 --> 42:35.070
<i>Gracias.</i>

42:39.900 --> 42:41.040
[DOGS WHIMPERING]

42:41.240 --> 42:42.350
[DOGS STOP BARKING]

42:42.550 --> 42:43.690
[SIGHS]

43:08.970 --> 43:10.670
- [ELECTRICITY CRACKLING]
- [SCREAMING]

43:13.460 --> 43:15.460
[DANCE MUSIC PLAYING DISTANTLY]

43:28.170 --> 43:29.780
[DOOR SQUEAKING]

43:32.740 --> 43:34.170
[TOILET FLUSHING]

43:39.610 --> 43:41.090
[WATER RUNNING]

44:01.370 --> 44:02.590
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

44:11.770 --> 44:12.950
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

44:19.170 --> 44:21.090
[ITEMS CLINKING]

44:23.920 --> 44:25.530
[GABRIELA BREATHING HEAVILY]

44:30.100 --> 44:31.530
[DOOR CREAKING]

44:39.280 --> 44:40.930
[GRUNTS]

44:43.760 --> 44:44.980
[GROANING]

44:46.420 --> 44:48.380
- [SCREAMING]
- [SPRAYING]

44:52.380 --> 44:55.870
CECILIA: I'm arranging
a small team in Bolivia
next week, Margaret.

44:56.070 --> 44:59.220
Yeah, we have three cases
scheduled already.

44:59.420 --> 45:02.440
But I think that we might
have room for one more spot.

45:02.640 --> 45:04.440
Yeah. We're working
off the grid, of course,

45:04.640 --> 45:07.480
but if you think
you can get there, Margaret.

45:09.960 --> 45:13.440
No... Please,
no need to cry, Margaret.

45:14.920 --> 45:17.810
No... [CHUCKLES]
I'm not an angel.

45:18.010 --> 45:19.320
It's pure science.

45:20.410 --> 45:22.810
All right.

45:23.010 --> 45:26.020
You send those medical records
in and we'll have a look,
all right?

45:26.890 --> 45:27.850
Perfect.

45:29.070 --> 45:30.160
See you soon, Margaret.

45:30.900 --> 45:31.850
See you soon.

45:32.770 --> 45:33.730
[CELL PHONE BEEPS]

45:38.510 --> 45:39.910
[DISTANT THUDDING]

45:41.260 --> 45:43.650
[RADIO ANNOUNCER
SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

45:47.910 --> 45:49.090
[DISTANT THUDDING]

46:50.110 --> 46:51.190
I've got a gun!

47:25.790 --> 47:27.890
- [GLASS SHATTERING]
- [SCREAMING]

47:28.090 --> 47:29.980
[BREATHING HEAVILY]

47:30.180 --> 47:32.060
[TENSE MUSIC PLAYING]

47:44.680 --> 47:46.160
[GARAGE DOOR OPENING]

47:47.030 --> 47:48.380
[CAR STARTING]

47:50.650 --> 47:51.990
What the fuck...

47:54.870 --> 47:55.870
[GASPS]

48:11.230 --> 48:12.230
Hi.

48:14.320 --> 48:15.540
Who are you?

48:16.710 --> 48:18.860
This is my associate, Amanda.

48:19.060 --> 48:20.680
[VALENTINA SCREAMING]

48:22.460 --> 48:23.850
- [GRUNTS]
- [YELPS]

48:24.850 --> 48:26.770
- [ELECTRICITY CRACKLING]
- [SCREAMS]

48:31.250 --> 48:32.860
[GRUNTING]

48:36.560 --> 48:38.690
Get some rest, Cecilia.

48:40.000 --> 48:42.180
You're going to
fucking need it.

48:46.220 --> 48:48.180
- [MAN SCREAMING]
- [CHAIN CLANGING]

48:52.880 --> 48:54.070
Mateo.

48:54.270 --> 48:56.240
[GRUNTS] What the fuck
is going on?

48:56.440 --> 48:57.930
[SCREAMING]
Why are we back here?

48:59.150 --> 49:01.590
Oh, my God. What the...

49:01.790 --> 49:04.120
- [MATEO CONTINUES SCREAMING]
- [CHAINS CLANKING]

49:04.320 --> 49:05.500
[GROANS]

49:08.030 --> 49:11.170
MATEO: Oh, my God. Oh, my God.
Help. Who are you?

49:11.370 --> 49:14.350
- Do you know why we're here?
- Hey! Hey.

49:14.550 --> 49:16.700
- MATEO: Lady, do you know...
- [GABRIELA SPEAKS IN SPANISH]

49:16.900 --> 49:17.830
Do you know who
brought us here?

49:18.030 --> 49:19.260
[VALENTINA SPEAKING IN SPANISH]

49:19.460 --> 49:21.440
MATEO: [IN ENGLISH]
Hey! Can you help us?

49:21.640 --> 49:22.560
[GROANS]

49:27.700 --> 49:30.620
Who are you?
Please. Please, please.

49:30.820 --> 49:32.620
- [GROANING]
- Hey, hey...

49:40.150 --> 49:41.580
What... What are you doing?

49:42.240 --> 49:44.150
[RATTLING]

49:47.410 --> 49:48.420
GABRIELA: Hey.

49:49.200 --> 49:50.160
[DOOR SLAMS]

49:53.290 --> 49:54.290
John?

49:55.510 --> 49:56.770
It was you?

49:57.600 --> 49:58.900
[SCREAMING] Why?

50:00.080 --> 50:01.340
Why are we here?

50:02.820 --> 50:03.820
CECILIA: John!

50:04.650 --> 50:06.490
What is this?

50:06.690 --> 50:08.610
We were only trying
to help you.

50:09.960 --> 50:11.660
That game is over.

50:11.860 --> 50:13.610
And a new game is
about to begin.

50:17.100 --> 50:18.670
- Valentina...
- [WHIMPERING]

50:18.870 --> 50:20.660
...did my blood ever
make it to the lab?

50:21.360 --> 50:23.070
<i>Or...</i>

50:23.270 --> 50:25.970
did you just suck it out
and flush it down
the drain somewhere?

50:26.580 --> 50:27.810
[WHIMPERING]

50:28.010 --> 50:29.730
MATEO: Mr. Kramer. Mr. Kramer.

50:29.930 --> 50:31.640
Please, listen to me.
I beg you.

50:31.840 --> 50:33.630
I beg you, please. Please.

50:34.980 --> 50:36.560
We have nothing
to do with this.

50:36.760 --> 50:38.600
We didn't know what was
going on. It was all her.

50:38.800 --> 50:40.560
She planned the whole thing.

50:40.760 --> 50:44.830
Mateo, I don't even know
if that's your real name.

50:45.030 --> 50:47.470
- It is my real name.
- It is, oh.

50:49.220 --> 50:52.530
'Cause they have never heard
of you at the hospital.

50:52.730 --> 50:54.060
She told me to say that
I worked there.

50:54.250 --> 50:57.010
- But I don't. I'm sorry.
- JOHN: Mm, mm.

50:57.210 --> 50:59.660
- MATEO: Please wait.
Let me explain.
- Mr. Kramer...

51:02.530 --> 51:04.850
I meant no harm.

51:05.050 --> 51:08.940
I would really like
to believe you, Gabriela.

51:09.140 --> 51:11.380
[SOBBING]

51:11.580 --> 51:13.330
You'll have a chance
to prove yourself.

51:14.850 --> 51:17.680
<i>Por favor. Por favor.</i>

51:19.680 --> 51:21.120
[WHIMPERING QUIETLY]

51:29.600 --> 51:32.080
The key to your freedom
is inside that box.

51:36.390 --> 51:37.660
What the hell is that?

51:37.860 --> 51:39.700
It's a Gigli saw.

51:41.220 --> 51:42.840
I thought you said
there was a key?

51:43.040 --> 51:44.930
He was speaking metaphorically.

51:45.130 --> 51:46.840
He does that a lot.

51:48.320 --> 51:50.330
When I get out of here,

51:50.530 --> 51:53.450
